# UX Anti-Patterns — Never Propose These

## Forms

- Never use placeholder text as a label replacement
- Never require fields that could be optional or inferred
- Never reset a form on validation error
- Never use dropdowns for fewer than 4 options (use radio/chips instead)

## Mobile

- Never use hover states as the only affordance
- Never put primary actions only at the top of a long page
- Never use full-screen modals for simple confirmations
- Never show empty disabled states — hide or explain them

## Feedback

- Never use generic errors ("Something went wrong")
- Never auto-dismiss success toasts in under 3 seconds
- Never show a spinner with no timeout/fallback
- Never leave users on the same screen after a destructive action

## Information Architecture

- Never nest navigation more than 3 levels deep
- Never use jargon in user-facing labels
- Never show more than one primary action per screen
- Never mix action types in a single button group (save + delete together)

## Trust and Safety

- Never permanently delete without a recovery window
- Never auto-submit a form
- Never change a user's data silently without a visible indicator
